ADO-EKITI – The Ekiti State Government has commended process of implementation of Supreme Court judge ordered the relocation of council headquarters of Ilejemeje from its present site in Iye to the new site Eda Oniyo. The seven-man Committee set up by the government on Monday visited the old and new sites and chaired by the Deputy Governor, Otunba Bisi Egbeyemi, who had an interface with the people of the two communities and urged them to give peace a chance in the wake of the apex court’s verdict. According to a statement signed by his Special Assistant (Media), Odunayo Ogunmola, Egbeyemi said the panel visited the two communities to assess what was on the ground having received documents from both parties. Egbeyemi explained that the visit was part of the assignment of the panel that would turn in its report to Governor Kayode Fayemi. The deputy governor stressed that the government was interested in ensuring that peace reigns in all communities in the state appealing to indigenes of Iye and Eda Oniyo not to engage in any act that could lead to the breakdown of law and order. The Supreme Court in a judgment delivered by Justice Bode Rhodes-Vivour on 14th December 2018 ordered the relocation of Ilejemeje council headquarters from Iye to Eda Oniyo ending a 19-year-old the battle which began at the State High Court. The apex court held that the establishment of the headquarters of the Local Government in Eda Oniyo was backed by statute and could not be relocated elsewhere without the promulgation of a new law.